Sizwezakhe VumazonkePicture: Screengrab / YouTube
Suspected hitman Sizwezakhe Vumazonke took a keen interest in Jayde Panayiotou’s murder investigation prior to his arrest.
A quick search history on the now deceased Vumazonke’s handset shows how he frequently Googled progress on the high-profile murder investigation.
According to information extracted from his cellphone, and now before the Port Elizabeth High Court, on April 28 2015, just days after Jayde’s murder, Vumazonke typed Jayde’s name into the Google search engine.
This led him to news articles titled “Shock at teacher’s murder”, “Task team set up to find Eastern Cape teacher’s killers”, as well as “Murdered teacher’s funeral to be held”.


On April 30, he read an article titled “Jayde Panayiotou’s husband arrested for murder”.
Then, on May 1, he read “Several people questioned over Jayde’s murder”, and Googled “another image of Jayde suspect released”.
The final article he read prior to his June 2015 arrest was titled “Jayde’s husband arrested”.
Vumazonke, 31, died in September last year, before the trial got under way.


